snippet.textDisplay: Blow guns with tranq darts are primarily used when researching large wild animals. They do, of course, have a very niche use in veterinary medicine, such as sedating an agitated bull elephant in a zoo to suture his lacerated cheek, or knocking out a tiger at a wildlife refuge to extract an infected tooth. Just a couple of examples. Mostly, wildlife researchers use blow guns and tranq darts to help with collecting data on large wild animals. This includes placing radio collars or other RF trackers to monitor the animals' roaming habits.
